lo RJ |title=First report of ''Penicillium allii'' as a field pathogen of garlic (''Allium sativum'') |journal=Plant Pathology |year=2006 |volume=55 |issue=4 |page=583 |doi=10.1111/j.1365-3059.2006.01411.x}}</ref>}}\n\n* {{cite book |last=Harshberger |first=J. W. |title=A Text-Book of Mycology and Plant Pathology |url=https://archive.org/details/atextbookmycolo00harsgoog |location=London |publisher=Churchill Livinstone |year=1917 |oclc=879097707}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikispecies}}\n\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3KJewsIL5vQC&pg=PA66&dq=genus+penicillium#v=onepage&q=genus%20penicillium&f=false |last=Samson |first=R.A. |first2=J.I. |last2=Pitt |title=Integration of Modern Taxonomic Methods For Penicillium and Aspergillus Classification |isbn=978-9058231598 |publisher=CRC Press |year=2000 |page=66 }}\n* {{cite journal |last=Asan |first=A. |year=2004 |title=''Aspergillus'', ''Penicillium'', and Related Species Reported from Turkey |journal=Mycotaxon |volume=89 |issue=1 |pages=155\u20137 |url=http://www.mycotaxon.com/resources/checklists/asan-v89-checklist.pdf }}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q843136}}\n\n[[Category:Medicinal fungi]]\n[[Category:Penicillium]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Johann Heinrich Friedrich Link]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toMold(link changed toMold (fungus)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Penicillium"}
{"title_page": "Rigby's Water World", "text_new": "{{short description|Water park in Georgia, U.S.}}\n{{Infobox amusement park\n|name = Rigby's Water World\n|image = Rigby's Water Park.jpg\n|caption =\n|location = [[Warner Robins, Georgia]], United States\n|coordinates = {{coord|32.550462|-83.686837|source:Doncram|display=inline,title}}\n|homepage = {{Official website|http://www.rigbysec.com/attractions/rigby-s-water-world}}\n|owner = Steve Rigby<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bellinghamherald.com/news/local/article162520053.html|title=Water park will feature 16 slides attached to one structure|publisher=}}</ref>\n|opening_date = July 7, 2018\n|season = May through September\n|area = {{convert|23|acre|m2}}<ref name=willopen>{{cite news|url=http://www.macon.com/news/local/community/houston-peach/article162692693.html#storylink=cpy|title=New water park will open this year, owner says}}</ref>\n|rides = 16\n}}\n'''Rigby's Water World''' is a {{convert|23|acre|m2|adj=on}} [[water park]] that opened in 2018. It is located in the southern part of [[Warner Robins, Georgia]], in [[Houston County, Georgia|Houston County]].\n\nIt was claimed, during its planning, that it would be \"the largest water park structure in the world\". The facility was to be a maze of 16 water slides and walkways with more than 40 water-play implements.<ref name=willopen/>\n\nFurther plans included an adult pool with a three-tier waterfall, a palm tree, and three children's pools. Two hotels, a 1,250-person convention center, a 250-seat restaurant, and a 6,000-person amphitheater were also planned,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sunherald.com/news/local/article162520053.html|title=Water park will feature 6 slides attached to one structure|publisher=}}</ref> but have not been built as of 2020.\n\nIt hosted a rock and country music festival in September 2019,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.13wmaz.com/article/entertainment/events/rigbys-holds-new-water-park-music-festival/93-b8291bd1-fe6d-420b-82c8-c121e83126e7 |title=Rigby's to hold music festival at Water World |author=Thais Ackerman |date=September 12, 2019|publisher=[[13 WMAZ]] |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref> and was to host the 62nd Annual Warner Robins Christmas Parade in December 2019, which would end at the park.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://41nbc.com/2019/09/26/rigbys-water-world-kick-off-62nd-annual-warner-robins-christmas-parade/ |title=Rigby\u2019S Water World to Kick Off 62nd Annual Warner Robins Christmas Parade |publisher=[[41 WMGT]] |author=Rashaad Vann |date=September 26, 2019 |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Development and 2018 opening==\n''Rigby's Water World'' opened on July 7, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.13wmaz.com/article/news/local/rigbys-water-world-in-warner-robins-is-finally-open-to-the-public/93-571609026 |title=Rigby's Water World in Warner Robins is finally open to the public |publisher=[[WMAZ]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.41nbc.com/2018/07/09/rigbys-water-world-makes-debut-splash-public/|title=Rigby's Water World makes its debut splash to the public - 41NBC News - WMGT-DT|date=9 July 2018|publisher=}}</ref> It contains a 750-gallon water bucket, seventeen slides, and water gadgets for kids.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.11alive.com/article/news/nation-world/rigbys-water-world-in-warner-robins-is-finally-open-to-the-public/85-571674349 |title=Rigby's Water World in Warner Robins is finally open to the public |author=Nicole Butler |date=July 7, 2018 |publisher=11alive}}</ref>\n\nRigby's Water World was about a $15 million development project.  \n\nA competitor, the Sandy Beach Water Park, opened after less than a $2 million investment but failed financially, and in 2017 the local government in its area was contemplating taking it over and reopening it.<ref name=\"dunlap\">{{cite web|url=https://www.macon.com/news/local/article187507853.html |publisher=[[The Telegraph (Macon)|The Telegraph]] |author=Stanley Dunlap |accessdate=July 18, 2018 |date=December 1, 2017 |title=Sandy Beach Water Park up for sale, but will any buyers take the plunge?}}</ref>\n\nThe development was anticipated to be one of the largest [[waterpark]] in the state of [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]].  \"There\u2019s not a whole lot to do in Middle Georgia, and this would be very welcome\", commented one Rigby waterpark official in June 2018.  During testing pre-opening, a \"boomerang slide\" appeared to be the favorite out of 16 slides in the park. Its [[lazy river]] is {{convert|1,600|ft|m}} long, {{convert|15|ft|m}} wide, and holds almost {{convert|1,000,000|gal|m3}} of water.<ref name=\"massive\">{{cite news |url=https://www.41nbc.com/2018/06/22/opening-soon-massive-water-park-warner-robins/ |publisher=[[WMGT-TV]]|title=Opening Soon: Massive Water Park in Warner Robins:  Rigby's water park is close to opening| author=Tanya Modersitzki |date=June 22, 2018 }}</ref> \n\nIn August 2018, the park was forced to shut down temporarily due to reports of a child testing positive for [[cryptosporidium]]. \n\nThe health department was notified and a [[state health agency]] investigation began.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.macon.com/news/local/community/houston-peach/article216675790.html|title=Multiple parasite cases linked to Warner Robins water park|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.13wmaz.com/article/news/local/state-investigating-health-complaints-at-rigbys-water-world/93-584039855|title=State investigating health complaints at Rigby's Water World|publisher=[[13 WMAZ]]}}</ref> After the investigation, the park owner claimed that the park was safe and free of waterborne disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.41nbc.com/2018/08/17/rigbys-water-world-owners-say-water-safe-parasite-complaints/|title=Rigby's Water World owners say water is safe after parasite complaints - 41NBC News - WMGT-DT|date=17 August 2018|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Water parks in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Warner Robins, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Houston County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Houston County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:2018 establishments in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Water park in Georgia, U.S.}}\n{{Infobox amusement park\n|name = Rigby's Water World\n|image = Rigby's Water Park.jpg\n|caption =\n|location = [[Warner Robins, Georgia]], United States\n|coordinates = {{coord|32.550462|-83.686837|source:Doncram|display=inline,title}}\n|homepage = {{Official website|http://www.rigbysec.com/attractions/rigby-s-water-world}}\n|owner = Steve Rigby<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bellinghamherald.com/news/local/article162520053.html|title=Water park will feature 16 slides attached to one structure|publisher=}}</ref>\n|opening_date = July 7, 2018\n|season = May through September\n|area = {{convert|23|acre|m2}}<ref name=willopen>{{cite news|url=http://www.macon.com/news/local/community/houston-peach/article162692693.html#storylink=cpy|title=New water park will open this year, owner says}}</ref>\n|rides = 16\n}}\n'''Rigby's Water World''' is a {{convert|23|acre|m2|adj=on}} [[water park]] that opened in 2018. It is located in the southern part of [[Warner Robins, Georgia]], in [[Houston County, Georgia|Houston County]].\n\nIt was claimed, during its planning, that it would be \"the largest water park structure in the world\". The facility was to be a maze of 16 water slides and walkways with more than 40 water-play implements.<ref name=willopen/>\n\nFurther plans included an adult pool with a three-tier waterfall, a palm tree, and three children's pools. Two hotels, a 1,250-person convention center, a 250-seat restaurant, and a 6,000-person amphitheater were also planned,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sunherald.com/news/local/article162520053.html|title=Water park will feature 6 slides attached to one structure|publisher=}}</ref> but have not been built as of 2020.\n\nIt hosted a rock and country music festival in September 2019,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.13wmaz.com/article/entertainment/events/rigbys-holds-new-water-park-music-festival/93-b8291bd1-fe6d-420b-82c8-c121e83126e7 |title=Rigby's to hold music festival at Water World |author=Thais Ackerman |date=September 12, 2019|publisher=[[13 WMAZ]] |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref> and was to host the 62nd Annual Warner Robins Christmas Parade in December 2019, which would end at the park.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://41nbc.com/2019/09/26/rigbys-water-world-kick-off-62nd-annual-warner-robins-christmas-parade/ |title=Rigby\u2019S Water World to Kick Off 62nd Annual Warner Robins Christmas Parade |publisher=[[41 WMGT]] |author=Rashaad Vann |date=September 26, 2019 |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Development and 2018 opening==\n''Rigby's Water World'' opened on July 7, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.13wmaz.com/article/news/local/rigbys-water-world-in-warner-robins-is-finally-open-to-the-public/93-571609026 |title=Rigby's Water World in Warner Robins is finally open to the public |publisher=[[WMAZ]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.41nbc.com/2018/07/09/rigbys-water-world-makes-debut-splash-public/|title=Rigby's Water World makes its debut splash to the public - 41NBC News - WMGT-DT|date=9 July 2018|publisher=}}</ref> It contains a 750-gallon water bucket, seventeen slides, and water gadgets for kids.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.11alive.com/article/news/nation-world/rigbys-water-world-in-warner-robins-is-finally-open-to-the-public/85-571674349 |title=Rigby's Water World in Warner Robins is finally open to the public |author=Nicole Butler |date=July 7, 2018 |publisher=11alive}}</ref>\n\nRigby's Water World was about a $15 million development project.  \n\nA competitor, the Sandy Beach Water Park, opened after less than a $2 million investment but failed financially, and in 2017 the local government in its area was contemplating taking it over and reopening it.<ref name=\"dunlap\">{{cite web|url=https://www.macon.com/news/local/article187507853.html |publisher=[[The Telegraph (Macon)|The Telegraph]] |author=Stanley Dunlap |accessdate=July 18, 2018 |date=December 1, 2017 |title=Sandy Beach Water Park up for sale, but will any buyers take the plunge?}}</ref>\n\nThe development was anticipated to be one of the largest [[waterpark]] in the state of [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]].  \"There\u2019s not a whole lot to do in Middle Georgia, and this would be very welcome\", commented one Rigby waterpark official in June 2018.  During testing pre-opening, a \"boomerang slide\" appeared to be the favorite out of 16 slides in the park. Its [[lazy river]] is {{convert|1,600|ft|m}} long, {{convert|15|ft|m}} wide, and holds almost {{convert|1,000,000|gal|m3}} of water.<ref name=\"massive\">{{cite news |url=https://www.41nbc.com/2018/06/22/opening-soon-massive-water-park-warner-robins/ |publisher=[[WMGT-TV]]|title=Opening Soon: Massive Water Park in Warner Robins:  Rigby's water park is close to opening| author=Tanya Modersitzki |date=June 22, 2018 }}</ref> \n\nIn August 2018, the park was forced to shut down temporarily due to reports of a child testing positive for [[cryptosporidium]]. \n\nThe health department was notified and a [[state health agency]] investigated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.macon.com/news/local/community/houston-peach/article216675790.html|title=Multiple parasite cases linked to Warner Robins water park|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.13wmaz.com/article/news/local/state-investigating-health-complaints-at-rigbys-water-world/93-584039855|title=State investigating health complaints at Rigby's Water World|publisher=[[13 WMAZ]]}}</ref> After the investigation, the park owner claimed that the park was safe and free of waterborne disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.41nbc.com/2018/08/17/rigbys-water-world-owners-say-water-safe-parasite-complaints/|title=Rigby's Water World owners say water is safe after parasite complaints - 41NBC News - WMGT-DT|date=17 August 2018|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Water parks in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Warner Robins, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Houston County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Houston County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:2018 establishments in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n", "name_user": "HuyyBoii 05", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rigby%27s_Water_World"}
{"title_page": "Food drying", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{more citations needed|date=June 2011}}\n{{generalize|date=July 2013|reason=mainly about grain drying}}\n}}\n\n[[File:Fish drying in the sun poisson seche Madagascar.jpg|thumb|150px|alt=rows of fish hang from string, drying in the sun |Flattened [[fish]] drying in the sun in [[Madagascar]]. Fish are [[Food preservation|preserved]] through such traditional methods as drying, [[Smoking (cooking)|smoking]] and [[Salting (food)|salting]].<ref name = smoke>Grandidier (1899), p. 521</ref>]]\n[[Image:Potato - dehydrated and sliced.jpg|right|thumb|150px|A whole potato, sliced pieces (right), and dried sliced pieces (left)]]\n\n'''Food drying''' is a method of [[food preservation]] in which food is [[drying|dried]] (dehydrated or [[desiccation|desiccated]]). Drying inhibits the growth of [[bacteria]], [[yeast]]s, and [[Mold (fungus)|mold]] through the removal of [[water]]. Dehydration has been used widely for this purpose since ancient times; the earliest known practice is 12,000 B.C. by inhabitants of the modern Middle East and Asia regions.<ref name=\"uog\">[http://www.uga.edu/nchfp/publications/nchfp/factsheets/food_pres_hist.html \"Historical Origins of Food Preservation\".] Accessed June 2011.</ref> Water is traditionally removed through [[evaporation]] (air drying, sun drying, smoking or wind drying), although today electric [[food dehydrator]]s or [[freeze-drying]] can be used to speed the drying process and ensure more consistent results.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Rahman |editor1-first=M. Shafiur |title=Handbook of Food Preservation |date=2007 |publisher=CRC Press |location=Boca Raton |isbn=9781420017373 |edition=2nd |language=English}}</ref> \n[[File:1890 newspaper advertisement showing tin of desiccated cocoanut.jpg|thumb|upright|1890 newspaper advertisement showing tin of dried coconut]]\n\n== Food types ==\n[[File:Dried mushrooms.jpg|thumb|A collection of dried mushrooms]]\n[[File:Octopus drying under the sun in Greece.jpg|thumb|170px|Sun-drying [[octopus]]]]\nMany different foods can be prepared by dehydration. Meat has held a historically significant role. For centuries, much of the European diet depended on dried [[cod]]\u2014known as [[dried and salted cod|salt cod]], [[bacalhau]] (with salt), or [[stockfish]] (without). It formed the main protein source for the [[slavery|slaves]] on the [[West Indies|West Indian]] plantations, and was a major economic force within the [[triangular trade]]. Dried fish most commonly cod or haddock, known as [[Har\u00f0fiskur]], is a delicacy in [[Iceland]], while dried [[reindeer]] meat is a traditional [[Sami people|Sami]] [[food]]. Dried meats include [[prosciutto]] ([[Parma ham]]), [[bresaola]], [[biltong]] and [[beef jerky]].\n\nDried fruits have been consumed historically due to their high sugar content and sweet taste, and a longer [[shelf-life]] from drying.<ref>{{cite book|isbn=978-0805052473|title=The Food Chronology: A Food Lover's Compendium of Events and Anecdotes from Prehistory to the Present|author=Trager, James|publisher=Henry Holt|year=1997}}</ref> [[Fruit]]s may be used differently when dried. The plum becomes a [[prune (fruit)|prune]], the grape a [[raisin]]. [[ficus|Fig]]s and [[date palm|date]]s may be transformed into different products that can either be eaten as they are, used in recipes, or rehydrated.\n\nFreeze-dried vegetables are often found in food for backpackers, hunters, and the military. [[Garlic]] and [[onion]] are often dried. Edible mushrooms, as well as other [[fungi]], are also sometimes dried for preservation purposes or to be used as seasonings.\n\n== Preparation ==\nHome drying of vegetables, fruit and meat can be carried out with electrical dehydrators (household appliance) or by sun-drying or by wind.<ref>{{cite web|title=Food Dehydrator reviews|url=http://dehydratorjudge.com/|publisher=www.dehydratorjudge.com|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref> Preservatives such as [[potassium metabisulfite]], [[butylated hydroxyanisole|BHA]], or [[butylated hydroxytoluene|BHT]] may be used, but are not required. However, dried products without these preservatives may require refrigeration or freezing to ensure safe storage for a long time.\n\nIndustrial food dehydration is often accomplished by [[freeze-drying]]. In this case food is [[flash freezing|flash frozen]] and put into a reduced-pressure system which causes the water to [[Sublimation (chemistry)|sublimate]] directly from the solid to the gaseous phase. Although freeze-drying is more expensive than traditional dehydration techniques, it also mitigates the change in flavor, texture, and [[Nutritional rating systems|nutritional value]]. In addition, another widely used industrial method of drying of food is convective hot air drying. Industrial hot air dryers are simple and easy to design, construct and maintain. More so, it is very affordable and has been reported to retain most of the nutritional properties of food if dried using appropriate drying conditions.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Modeling the thin-layer drying of fruits and vegetables: A review |date=2016-02-04 |doi=10.1111/1541-4337.12196 |volume=15 |issue=3 |journal=Comprehensive Reviews in Food Science and Food Safety |pages=599\u2013618|last1 = Onwude|first1 = Daniel I.|last2=Hashim |first2=Norhashila |last3=Janius |first3=Rimfiel B. |last4=Nawi |first4=Nazmi Mat |last5=Abdan |first5=Khalina |url=http://psasir.upm.edu.my/id/eprint/15197/1/Modeling%20the%20thin%E2%80%90layer%20drying%20of%20fruits%20and%20vegetables%20a%20review.pdf }}</ref>\n\nAnother form of food dehydration is irradiation. Irradiation uses x-rays, ultraviolet light, and ionizing radiations to penetrate food to the point of sterilization. Astronauts and people who are highly at risk for microbial infections benefit from this method of food drying.\n\n[[Hurdle technology]] is the combination of multiple food preservation methods. Hurdle technology uses low doses of multiple food preservation techniques in order to ensure food is not only safe but is desirable visually and texturally.\n\n== Packaging ==\nPackaging ensures effective food preservation. Some methods of packaging that are beneficial to dehydrated food are vacuum sealed, inert gases, or gases that help regulate respiration, biological organisms, and growth of microorganisms.\n\n== Other methods ==\n[[File:Food dehydrator.jpg|thumb|150px|This electric [[food dehydrator]] has a hot air blower that blows air through trays with foods on them. Pictured are mango and papaya slices being dried.]]\nThere are many different methods for drying,<ref name=\"si\">{{cite journal|journal=J Sci Food Agric|year=2016|volume=96|issue=6|pages=2055\u201362|doi= 10.1002/jsfa.7317|title=Comparison of different drying methods on the physical properties, bioactive compounds and antioxidant activity of raspberry powders|authors=Si X, Chen Q, Bi J, Wu X, Yi J, Zhou L, Li Z|pmid=26108354}}</ref> each with their own advantages for particular applications. These include:\n{{Div col}}\n* [[convection|Convection drying]]\n* [[Bed dryer]]s\n* [[Drum drying]]\n* [[Freeze Drying]]\n* [[microwave oven|Microwave-vacuum drying]]<ref name=si/>\n* [[Shelf dryer]]s\n* [[Spray drying]]\n* [[infrared|Infrared radiation drying]]<ref name=si/>\n* [[Combined thermal hybrid drying]]<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://zenodo.org/record/895601 |title=Recent advances of novel thermal combined hot air drying of agricultural crops |date=2016-10-30 |accessdate=2017-03-25 |doi=10.1016/j.tifs.2016.09.012 |volume=57 |issue=A |journal=Trends in Food Science & Technology |pages=132\u2013145|last1=Onwude |first1=Daniel I. |last2=Hashim |first2=Norhashila |last3=Chen |first3=Guangnan }}</ref>\n* [[Sunlight]]\n* Commercial [[food dehydrator]]s\n* Household [[oven]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Food}}\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Bouillon cube]]\n* [[Curing (food preservation)|Curing]]\n* [[Dried fruit]]\n* [[Instant noodles]]\n* [[Instant soup]]\n* [[List of dried foods]]\n* [[List of smoked foods]]\n* [[List of foods]]\n* [[Meat extract]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n<ref>\t\nMendonca, Aubrey F., and Norman N. Potter. \u201cFood Preservation.\u201d AccessScience, McGraw-Hill Education, 2016.</ref>\n\n== External links ==\n<references group=\"Mendonca, Aubrey F., and Norman N. Potter. \u201cFood Preservation.\u201d AccessScience, McGraw-Hill Education, 2016.\" />{{Commons category|Dried food}}\n* [http://nchfp.uga.edu/how/dry.html National Center for Home Food Preservation, drying section]\n\n{{Food preservation}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Drying (Food)}}\n[[Category:Cooking techniques]]\n[[Category:Drying processes]]\n[[Category:Food technology]]\n[[Category:Dried foods| ]]\n[[Category:Garde manger]]\n\n[[ca:Assecatge]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{more citations needed|date=June 2011}}\n{{generalize|date=July 2013|reason=mainly about grain drying}}\n}}\n\n[[File:Fish drying in the sun poisson seche Madagascar.jpg|thumb|150px|alt=rows of fish hang from string, drying in the sun |Flattened [[fish]] drying in the sun in [[Madagascar]]. Fish are [[Food preservation|preserved]] through such traditional methods as drying, [[Smoking (cooking)|smoking]] and [[Salting (food)|salting]].<ref name = smoke>Grandidier (1899), p. 521</ref>]]\n[[Image:Potato - dehydrated and sliced.jpg|right|thumb|150px|A whole potato, sliced pieces (right), and dried sliced pieces (left)]]\n\n'''Food drying''' is a method of [[food preservation]] in which food is [[drying|dried]] (dehydrated or [[desiccation|desiccated]]). Drying inhibits the growth of [[bacteria]], [[yeast]]s, and [[mold]] through the removal of [[water]]. Dehydration has been used widely for this purpose since ancient times; the earliest known practice is 12,000 B.C. by inhabitants of the modern Middle East and Asia regions.<ref name=\"uog\">[http://www.uga.edu/nchfp/publications/nchfp/factsheets/food_pres_hist.html \"Historical Origins of Food Preservation\".] Accessed June 2011.</ref> Water is traditionally removed through [[evaporation]] (air drying, sun drying, smoking or wind drying), although today electric [[food dehydrator]]s or [[freeze-drying]] can be used to speed the drying process and ensure more consistent results.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Rahman |editor1-first=M. Shafiur |title=Handbook of Food Preservation |date=2007 |publisher=CRC Press |location=Boca Raton |isbn=9781420017373 |edition=2nd |language=English}}</ref> \n[[File:1890 newspaper advertisement showing tin of desiccated cocoanut.jpg|thumb|upright|1890 newspaper advertisement showing tin of dried coconut]]\n\n== Food types ==\n[[File:Dried mushrooms.jpg|thumb|A collection of dried mushrooms]]\n[[File:Octopus drying under the sun in Greece.jpg|thumb|170px|Sun-drying [[octopus]]]]\nMany different foods can be prepared by dehydration. Meat has held a historically significant role. For centuries, much of the European diet depended on dried [[cod]]\u2014known as [[dried and salted cod|salt cod]], [[bacalhau]] (with salt), or [[stockfish]] (without). It formed the main protein source for the [[slavery|slaves]] on the [[West Indies|West Indian]] plantations, and was a major economic force within the [[triangular trade]]. Dried fish most commonly cod or haddock, known as [[Har\u00f0fiskur]], is a delicacy in [[Iceland]], while dried [[reindeer]] meat is a traditional [[Sami people|Sami]] [[food]]. Dried meats include [[prosciutto]] ([[Parma ham]]), [[bresaola]], [[biltong]] and [[beef jerky]].\n\nDried fruits have been consumed historically due to their high sugar content and sweet taste, and a longer [[shelf-life]] from drying.<ref>{{cite book|isbn=978-0805052473|title=The Food Chronology: A Food Lover's Compendium of Events and Anecdotes from Prehistory to the Present|author=Trager, James|publisher=Henry Holt|year=1997}}</ref> [[Fruit]]s may be used differently when dried. The plum becomes a [[pr